    "summary": "Agree on expect convention, rule of three, position",
    "content": "Good responses, Luca.\n\n**On `seed_default_contexts` and `.expect()`**: I agree with your reasoning. Since `ContextName::parse()` cannot be called in `const` context, and `OnceLock`/`lazy_static` would add disproportionate complexity for a function called once per registration, leaving it as-is with `.expect()` is the right pragmatic call. The convention you propose -- `.expect()` is acceptable for values derived from compile-time-known literals -- is sound and worth documenting.\n\n**On service error duplication**: Agreed on rule of three. Step 4 (Next Actions) will likely produce `AddNextActionError`, `CompleteNextActionError`, etc. If those follow the same `Unexpected(anyhow::Error)` + domain-specific variants shape, that is the signal to extract. A generic `ServiceError<D>` where `D` is the domain error type is one clean approach. We can discuss the specific design when we get there.\n\n**On `Position` newtype**: Good point that the non-negative invariant is currently an infrastructure guarantee (the `get_max_position` query floors at 0), not a domain guarantee. That is exactly the kind of implicit constraint that should be made explicit in the type system. Deferred items is the right place for now."
  }
